						               													<description>Spanish game for adults from the early 80s with ambiance in the &amp;quot;Barrio Chino&amp;quot; (Chinese Neighborhood, Spanish term for red light district) of Barcelona. With a mechanics like the Monopoly, the players play the role of prostitutes (whores), thieves and transsexuals.&amp;#10;The goal of this game is earn more money than others players(stealing, selling drugs or having sex) in a limit of time what must be choose by the players at the start of game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Juego espa&amp;ntilde;ol para adultos de principios de los 80 ambientado en el &amp;quot;Barrio Chino&amp;quot; de Barcelona, centro en aquella &amp;eacute;poca de prostituci&amp;oacute;n y drogas. Con una mec&amp;aacute;nica similar a la del Monopoly, los jugadores son prostitutas, chulos navajeros y travestis que deben ganar m&amp;aacute;s dinero que los dem&amp;aacute;s (robando, vendiendo drogas o acost&amp;aacute;ndose con clientes) en un l&amp;iacute;mite de tiempo que debe ser escogido en com&amp;uacute;n por los jugadores al principio.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;From &amp;quot;The New Spaniards&amp;quot; (Penguin Politics and Current Affairs version) by John Hooper pg. 150:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;        In a historic lapse of taste, a board game called El Chino was marketed in Spain in the early eighties. Players moved pieces representing pimps, whores and transvestites.  Those unlucky enough to catch a venereal disease had to be moved to a square marked 'clinic'&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
